My favorite dish from a recent dinner party - delicious. I used fresh Dungeness crab and fresh chanterelles from the farmer's market. There was no problem with overpowering the crab, as Dungeness is sweet and flavorful and can hold it's own. I grew up around the Chesapeake Bay and love Maryland Blues too, but there's no way you could taste the more delicate blue crab above the background of the other flavors in this soup. Definitely use Dungeness. I agree that the Chanterelles weren't worth it - there are plenty of other great Chanterelle recipes out there that use that mushroom to its advantage. Frankly, I would omit the mushrooms all together - they don't need a substitute.

Rating: 4
Wow! This is delicious! I made this as one of eight courses for our wine club, and it was a huge hit. I followed the hints of previous reviewers and made a few changes. I used only 1 cup of sweet onions and ¾ tsp fennel seeds so as not to overpower the crab. I also added 20 oz of frozen corn and used unpeeled new potatoes...I would use one or two fewer potatoes next time. I used deli bacon and also added ¾ tsp of Old Bay. I used 8 oz crimini mushrooms, as the only chanterelles available were dried and VERY expensive. I spent my money on fresh Dungeness crab instead and increased the amount to 1 ½ pounds which resulted in oohhs and aahhs. I made this about 3 hours ahead to allow for the flavors to blend before adding the crab and mushrooms, and served it with a rich, buttery chardonnay. I would certainly make this again, with the same changes, and serve it as the main course along with a salad and crusty bread.

